 changes in the roles of juries and appeals, the nature of prosecution and punishment, and the pattern of growing leniency, Eldridge also shows us why this expansion occurred when it did. He concludes that the ironic combination of tumult and destabilization on the one hand, and steady growth and development on the other, made colonists more willing to criticize authority openly and officials less able to prevent it. That, in turn, established a foundation for the more celebrated flowering of colonial dissent against English authority in the eighteenth century.Steeped in primary sources and richly narrated, this is an invaluable addition to the library of anyone interested in legal history, colonial America, or the birth of free speech in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aAfrican American intellectualsvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansxColonizationzLiberiaxHistoryy19th centuryvSources. 0aAfrican AmericansxColonizationzLiberiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPan-AfricanismxHistoryy19th centuryvSources. 0aPan-AfricanismxHistoryy19th century. 4aA. 4aDistant. 4aHeritage. 4acentury. 4acolonists. 4acriticize. 4adramatic. 4aduring. 4aexpansion. 4aexperienced. 4afreedom. 4agovernment. 4aoccurred. 4aofficials. 4aonly. 4aseventeenth. 4ashows. 4atheir. 4athis. 4awhen. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814722534423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814722534.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK